<br>
2. Practice. The more you practice the faster you'll get better. I try to get one sketch in my sketchbook a day. Not just of a face or a hand but a whole picture sketched. Keep your sketches.<br>
<br>
3. Don't aim for a particular style. If you do you'll probably just frusterate yourself. Just let your style evolve on it's own. I started out drawing manga but now it looks American. No regrets.<br>
<br>
4. Push yourself. Just as a body builder won't get better muscles by lifting the same wieght he started out at you'll never get better by drawing the same thing over and over with just a few variations on the same drawing.<br>
<br>
5. Take a drawing class and learn to see. Since I started my drawing class at college I have gotten much better in my personal work.<br>
<br>
6. Take life drawing. Hardest thing I'm doing. Not drawing a thing resembling what your looking at but drawing what your looking at. Difficult but helps. People are especially hard.<br>
<br>
7. Be loose. Be messy with your drawings in the early stages. I would recommend not to use stick figure or ball and cone method because it can make a person tighten up trying to draw a perfect stick figure or ball and cone person. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/umylak.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mylak</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/3/01 9:52:36 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://mylakovich.homestead.com/files/pics/ngpcjin.gif height= 71 width= 73></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Those are good suggestions.</span><hr size=1> I think everyone who is starting out should take this advice seriously.<br>
